authorization2star  aSince the Reagan presidency, more and more public policymaking authority has devolved to the states, a trend that the contributors to this volume argue is unlikely to abate soon. Public Opinion in State Politics is an innovative collection of recent research developed in response to signs of this growing importance of state politics. It updates and expands the previous work on public opinion and state politics, taking into account new data and methods, and drawing comparisons across states. The book is organized around three major themes: the conceptualization and measurement of public opinion in the states; explanations of variation in state public opinion; and the impact of public opinion on state politics and policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 0aState governmentszUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 4aPolitics -- Theory and Methods. 4aPolitics -- United States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / State.2bisacsh1 aBafumi, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrilleaux, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrace, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Jeffrey E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Jeffrey E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aErikson, Robert S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGelman, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaider-Markel, Donald P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamman, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacoby, William G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re